    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-06-20T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-06-20T00:00:00-05:00" n="82"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d82">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">
                    <persName corresp="#p_LFAWD1">Leahy</persName> Papers: Telegram</note>
                <head>No. 82 <lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Commanding General, United States Military Mission in the
                        Soviet Union</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_DMGJR1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Deane</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the Supreme Commander, Allied Expeditionary
                        Force</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_EGADD1" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Eisenhower</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret</hi>
                        <lb/>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">urgent</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-06-20">20 June
                            1945</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>To <gloss target="#t_ETOUSA1">ETOUSA</gloss> forward for <persName
                        corresp="#p_EGADD1">General Eisenhower</persName> and <gloss
                        target="#t_info1">info</gloss> to <gloss target="#t_AGWar1">AGWar</gloss>
                    for <persName corresp="#p_MGAGC1">General Marshall</persName>’s <gloss
                        target="#t_EyesOnly1">Eyes Only</gloss> signed <persName corresp="#p_DMGJR1"
                        >Deane</persName>
                    <gloss target="#t_topsec1">top sec</gloss>
                    <gloss target="#t_MX1">MX</gloss> 24748 copy sent all.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_HWA2">Harriman</persName> spoke to <persName
                        corresp="#p_V2">Vyshinski</persName> last night<note n="1" xml:id="d82fn1"
                        >See <ref target="#d78">document No. 78</ref>.</note> concerning the
                    necessity for <persName corresp="#p_PMGFL1">General Parks</persName>’
                    reconnaissance party to proceed to Berlin at once in order to make arrangements
                    for the American delegation at the Berlin July conference.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_V2">Vyshinski</persName> said it would be futile for
                        <persName corresp="#p_PMGFL1">Parks</persName> and his party to go to Berlin
                    prior to <persName corresp="#p_ZMGK1">Marshal Zhukov</persName>’s return, as
                    there were no Soviet officers left in Berlin who could act with authority on the
                    questions that would arise. <persName corresp="#p_V2">Vyshinski</persName> told
                        <persName corresp="#p_HWA2">Harriman</persName> that the Soviet authorities
                    were fully aware of the problems involved and that as soon as <persName
                        corresp="#p_ZMGK1">Zhukov</persName>
                    <pb facs="0244" n="112" xml:id="pg_112"/> returns to Berlin, intensive
                    preparations for the conference would start. <persName corresp="#p_V2"
                        >Vyshinski</persName> assured <persName corresp="#p_HWA2"
                        >Harriman</persName> that there was no need for worry.</p>
                <p>The British have had the same response to their efforts to introduce a
                    reconnaissance party to Berlin. <persName corresp="#p_MFMSB1">Field Marshal
                        Montgomery</persName> is sending a letter to <persName corresp="#p_ZMGK1"
                        >Zhukov</persName> on the same subject through the British Mission in
                    Moscow.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_HWA2">Harriman</persName> is again going to see <persName
                        corresp="#p_V2">Vyshinski</persName>, who is apparently to have an active
                    part in the conference preparations. At this meeting <persName corresp="#p_HWA2"
                        >Harriman</persName> will attempt to obtain the Russian views on the
                    arrangements for the conference.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_HWA2">Harriman</persName> may also suggest that he and
                        <persName corresp="#p_V2">Vyshinski</persName> go to Berlin together after
                        <persName corresp="#p_PMGFL1">General Parks</persName> has been in Berlin
                    for a few days, in the hope that he can obtain Soviet decisions on the spot that
                    will assist <persName corresp="#p_PMGFL1">General Parks</persName> in carrying
                    out his mission.</p>
                <p>You may wish to send a message to <persName corresp="#p_ZMGK1">Zhukov</persName>
                    which would include the major questions to which you require immediate answers.
                    If so, I will attempt to get such message to <persName corresp="#p_ZMGK1"
                        >Zhukov</persName> here in Moscow through <persName corresp="#p_AAGAI1"
                        >Antonov</persName>.</p>
            </div>
